        <bioghist id="ref1">
            <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
            <p>Christopher Wood joined the U.S. Coast Guard on July 14, 1969. He chose the Coast Guard because one of his friends had also enlisted, and he thought the chances of him going to Vietnam would be decreased. He went to the Coast Guard Academy in Cape May, NJ, where basic training lasted eight weeks and the seaman apprentices learned a myriad of skills. Just after finishing basic training, Wood was assigned to Cutter Chase, which was on its way to Vietnam. The cutter's home base was Subic Bay in the Philippines. From there the ships would deploy for 30-day patrols, where it was the Coast Guard's duty to stop the "flow of men and materials" from North Vietnam to South Vietnam. These patrols were known as "Operation Market Time"" Wood was stationed in Vietnam for ten months during which time Cutter Chase completed 7-8 patrols. When Wood returned to the United States, he attended radar school on Governor's Island, NY, and graduated as a petty officer with the title, Radarman. He was then transferred to the Cutter Campbell out of Portland, ME. Wood was discharged from the Coast Guard on August 24, 1972 after four years of service and returned to Connecticut.</p>
        </bioghist>
